You are hereby constituted as an Ad-Hoc Committee, with Mr. Derrick Nicdao as Chairman, to study the food service requirements in the College. Specifically, the task involve the following:
a.) Determine whether there is a need for a college canteen/eatery within Melchor Hall to serve the constituencies of the Colleges of Engineering and Architecture, considering the proximity of other such services in the immediate neighborhood;
b.) If the need is established, a possible and relatively good location is the area being currently used by the UFS plus the area to be vacated by the Property Office. Consider and study various options (UFS, CASAA-style, private concessions, etc.). Recommend the best option considering factors such as preference of the constituency, scope and quality of service, possible revenue to the College for the use of the "premium" space, which, otherwise could be used as classrooms or offices, etc.;
c.) Prepare and submit report on or before December 3, 1987. It should include recommendations.

As agreed upon during the meeting of the College Executive Committee last June 22, 1983, you are hereby constituted as the College Research Committee for academic year 1983-1984. The Committee will perform the following functions : 
1. Screen and recommend proposals for UPERDFI-funded research;
2. Screen and recommend publications that will be eligible for the UPERDFI cash awards;
3. Screen and recommend graduate fellows who will be eligible for UPERDFI financial support.

1. Permission for Mr. Nathaniel C. Lim are cross register as a research student in the University of Tokyo until June 1982; 
2. He shall report the progress of his work at least once every two months to his thesis adviser, Dr. Luis M. Alarilla, Jr., and he shall carry out whatever instructions Dr. Alarilla may give him regarding the research; and
3. Upon completion of the research, Mr. Lim shall defend his thesis before a thesis committee to be formed in accordance with the rules of the Graduate School of our University.

Please constitute yourselves into a Committee on Physical Facilities Improvement with Mr. Vallente as Chairman. The functions of the Committee  will be : 
1. To identify areas in the College of Engineering where physical improvement is needed;
2. To submit recommendations on priority improvement areas together with the financial requirements. Should there be a need for the services of other offices to accomplish this objective, the Committee can make the necessary recommendation for the Indorsement of the Dean.

Please be informed that you are hereby constituted into a College Committee on Physical Plant with Dr. Jose Azarcon, Jr. as Chairman. It will henceforth be one of the Standing Committees of the College. 
The functions of the Committee are : 
1. To recommend ways and means of improving the physical facilities of the College such as those related to power, water, communications and parking;
2. To develop an energy and water conservation program for the College;
3. To coordinate the improvement of such facilities;
4. To promote and monitor the efficient and effective utilization of these facilities.

I read with interest your article "Program for Solar Energy Utilization in the Philippines" in the 'Philippine Geographical Journal'
I have the pleasure to inform you that Prof. Dr. Gunther Lehner of the University of Stuttgart, Germany will come to Manila from March 4 to March 11, 1982 to conduct a series of lecture/seminars on Solar Energy. Please find enclosed some details on Dr. Lehner and his topics. 
The following lectures are in the planning stage :
1. UTILIZATION OF SOLAR ENERGY IN GERMANY, venue the Goethe-Institut, including a Solar Energy Exhibition to be opened by Dr. Lehner;
2. SELECTIVE LAYERING FOR SOLAR ABSORBERS, Partner : PAGASA, Dr. Roman Quintanal;
3. POTENTIAL AND PROBLEMS IN THE UTILIZATION OF SOLAR ENERGY; Partner : Bureau of Non-Conventional Energy, Dr. Ibarra Cruz;
4. SOLAR CELL SYSTEMS, Partner : Physics Society of the Phils. venue University of the Philippines;
5. CURRENT AND FUTURE PROSPECTS FOR THE COMMERCIAL AND INDUSTRIAL UTILIZATION OF SOLAR ENERGY, Partner : Asian Institute of Management, Dr. Mendoza. 
I have been informed that the U.P. College of Engineering is also deeply involved in Solar Energy Research. Please be so kind as to let me know at your earliest convenience whether your college is interested in coordinating one of the above mentioned lecture / seminars, or if you prefer to arrange a separate program with Dr. Lehner. There is no cost involved. Please be so kind as to give me a ring.

As per your request I am pleased to transmit hereunder a shopping list of institutions and areas in whch the College of Engineering would like to promote cooperation and assistance. In general, we wish to promote cooperation in the fields of education and academic research in those fields which will enhance each institution's educational and academic roles. The following activities can be explored : 
1. Joint research and exchange of scholars and researchers pertaining thereto;
2. Exchange of information and materials in those fields which are of interest to both Faculties;
3. Exchange of graduate students. 
Special areas of interests : 
1. Management and production techniques which are best suited to the resources and future development potential of developing countries;
2. Low-cost techniques which are compatible with local sociological conditions;
3. Development of alternative sources of energy;
4. Availability of training programs for engineering teachers from developing countries; 
5. Computers in engineering education;
6. Environmental impact assessment of development projects

REPUBLIC OF THE PHILIPPINES
QUEZON CITY
I, Crisostomo A. Ortigas, of legal age, married and residing at UP Campus, Diliman, after being duly sworn to in accordance with law, depose and say :
That from the year 1953 up to the year 1959 I was the project director of a number of NEC-ICA counterpart projects in the Diliman units of the University of the Philippines;
That as such project director, I received certain equipment under the terms of counterpart Projects listed as follows : 
(A) Rehabilitation of the U.P. College of Engineering including Geology, Chemistry, Physics, Industrial Pharmacy, bearing CP Nos. 20, 65, 430, 530, 630, 730, 830, 930;
(B) The University of the Philippines - Stanford University Contract involving the Colleges of Business Administration, Education, Engineering, Main Library, Physics, and Geology, bearing CP No. 492, 592, 692, 792, 892;
(C) The Electronics Training Project bearing CP No. 7103.
That the equipment received by me under the terms of the above enumerated projects as of 1959 were properly distributed to the Colleges of Business Administration, Education, Engineering, Liberal Arts, Main Library, and Pharmacy in pursuance of the terms of project agreements. 
That the equipment received by the responsible officers of the aforementioned colleges and units. 
That sometime in 1959 Dr. Vicente G. Sinco, the then incumbent president took over abruptly the authority on and the responsibilities pertaining to project directorship;
That on account of unavoidable time lag between approval of agreement on the one hand and implementation on the other, commodities continued to arrivel well beyond 1959;
That I am not fully acquainted with the procedures followed by the project director in distributing commodities that were received by him since he took over the responsibilities;
That I am aware that copies of inventories for NEC-ICA have been in the state of preparation since 1959 under the direction of the UP property officer and that I have extended unqualified cooperation in said preparation. 
IN WITNESS THEREOF, I have hereunto set my hand this 25 day of January, 1963, in the district of Diliman, Quezon City.

COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING
University of the Philippines
Diliman, Quezon City

23 November 1987

MEMORANDUM

For : All FACULTY MEMBERS
College of Engineering

From : The College Secretary

The 257th faculty meeting of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, 25 NOVEMBER 1987, 2:30-4:00 p.m. at MH 410. The agenda is as follows : 

(1) Approval of the minutes of the 256th meeting held on June 11, 1987;
(2) Business arising from the minutes: 
(3) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of the First Semester 1987-88;
(4) Action on Requests for Change of Grade;
(5) Curriculum Change Proposal (EE Dept.);
(6) Proposal to revise procedures on the Waiver of Maximum Residence Rule Requirements;
(7) Telecommunication Research and Service Institute Proposal;
(8) Other matters. 

ROMEO G. SOLIS

8 December 1986

